<paragraph pageId="23" pageNumber="40">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kerremans" baseAuthorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Bilyaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipennis" subGenus="Tomasia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="40">Bilyaxia (Tomasia) cinctipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. 13 Bilyaxia (Tomasia) maculicollis (Kerremans, 1887), female, 4.6 mm (Argentina, Entre Rios) 14 Bilyaxia (Tomasia) lata (Kerremans, 1903), male, 5.0 mm (Brasil, Rio Grande do Sul) 15 Bilyaxia (Tomasia) cinctipennis (Kerremans, 1913), male holotype, 7.0 mm 16 Brasilaxia costifera (Obenberger, 1913), male, 6.3 mm (Brasil, Curityba) 17 Paracuris bimaculata bimaculata (Gory, 1841), male, 7.1 mm (Argentina, Catamarca) 18 the same, female, 7.2 mm (Brasil, Bermejo)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/21690" pageId="23" pageNumber="40">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) somewhat contradicts the definition of the subgenus by its colouration (black and yellow pattern) and by the widely rounded elytral apices. In 2010 I found in Paraguay (Prov. Presidente Hayes) a specimen with entirely yellow elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
